Before, to have a polite conversation, one followed Henry Higgins' advice in "My Fair Lady": stick to the weather and your health.
But nowadays, with climate change and the anti-vaccination movement, these topics... are no longer very safe.
The world we live in, this world where any conversation can potentially evolve into controversy, where our politicians cannot talk to each other, and where even the most trivial subjects have supporters and detractors, this world is not normal.
Pew Research conducted a study on 10,000 American adults and found that, currently, we are more polarized, more divided, than ever before.
We make fewer compromises, which means that we do not listen to each other.
We decide where to live, who to marry, and even who our friends will be, based on our already established convictions.
Once again, this does not mean that we do not listen to each other.
A conversation requires a balance between speaking and listening, and somewhere along the way, we have lost this balance.
It is partly due to technology.
The cell phones that you all have, either in your hands or close enough to grab quickly.
According to Pew Research, about a third of American teenagers send more than 100 text messages per day.
Many of them, the majority in fact, will probably send a text message to their friends rather than talk to them face to face.
